<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Delays on DTI initiatives worry industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A backlog is building up on a number of important initiatives promised by
the Department of Trade and Industry, headed by Mr Michael Heseltine. The
delays  - some of many months  - are creating uncertainty and threatening to
damage business, according to industrialists.
The longest delay  - 21 months  - is over plans to privatise the Post
Office. The Post Office's future was reviewed by the DTI in the summer of
1992 but the department is yet to decide on how it should be privatised.
Other areas affected are the domestic gas market, where deregulation plans
are now several months overdue, and the power generation market, where a
review of the nuclear industry promised for last December has yet to
materialise.
Further initiatives which appear to have stalled include plans announced
last July to privatise the Patent Office and Companies House.
The DTI was last week unable to give any indication of when further
announcements on these initiatives might be expected.
A senior official said: 'With all these reviews it is more important to get
it right than stick to an artificial timetable. It is far worse to get it
wrong and publish quickly.
'The accusation that we have been dithering is unfair. We are determined to
publish the reviews in our own time and we will not be pushed by the outside
vested interests saying 'publish now, now, now'.'
Close colleagues of Mr Heseltine in the Commons argue that it would be
'political suicide' for him to publish the conclusions of some of the
reviews so soon before next month's local elections and June's elections to
the European parliament.
'The headlines would not be worth thinking about,' said one senior
backbencher, fearful that his constituents would link Post Office
privatisation to closure of rural post offices.
According to DTI officials, many of these measures have been held up by
technicalities and the weight of work on privatisations. In the case of the
nuclear review, a decision to expand the nuclear power industry could be
threatened by legal challenges.
Fear of a backlash in the local and European elections may also have been a
factor in the delay on gas deregulation which  - according to critics  -
could lead to price increases.
The delays are creating uncertainties among investors and managers in the
industries affected. In the gas industry, where dozens of independent
companies are gearing up for the planned ending of British Gas's monopoly,
the delay is holding up investment decisions.
In the nuclear industry, where state-owned Nuclear Electric is hoping to be
privatised, there is concern that the delay in the nuclear review could
indicate that privatisation might be scrapped as too controversial.
Details, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
<XX>
