<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Food &amp; Drink: A venture into white - Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Drinking at a first-growth chateau can be a mite limited - all that dry red.
No wonder then that more of Bordeaux's superstars are venturing into white
wine territory.
Pavillon Blanc de Chateau Margaux was followed by Ch Mouton-Rothschild's
Aile d'Argent dry white (the second vintage, 1992, much less oaky than the
first) and now Mouton announces a close working relationship with the
Sauternes property Ch Coutet.
Not to be outdone, Ch Latour has launched its own dry white, Blanc de
Pauillac 1992, yours for Pounds 300 a dozen from Farr Vintners of London SW1
(071-828-1960). Those who cook at Pauillac's smartest addresses should be
thrilled by the chance to experiment with dishes that go with something
other than claret. Jancis Robinson
                           *       *      *
An historical success story from South Africa was the famous Constantia wine
which was loved by just about everyone before the vineyards were wiped out
by phylloxera at the end of the 19th century.
For the best part of a century the secrets of Constantia were lost, but in
1980 Klein Constantia replanted Muscadel vines with the intention of
recreating the famous wine. The first new vintage was made in 1986. The
current, 1989, is therefore the fourth.
You might be put off by the pseudo-18th century 500ml bottles, but the wine
inside is superb; a rather delicate brew considering its 15 or so degrees
with a lasting orange and peach flavour.
Klein Constantia's 'vin de Constance' is available from Averys of Bristol
(tel: 0272-214141).
The price is Pounds 10.66 a bottle, Pounds 126.20 a case. Giles MacDonogh
                           *       *      *
For top quality Sauvignon Blanc, an obvious - if apparently expensive -
candidate is Mulderbosch Sauvignon Blanc from South Africa. At Pounds 86 a
case from John Armit Wines of London W11 (071-727-6846) it is first-class
wine: full-bodied, serious, and intriguingly - but certainly not offensively
 -aromatic.
Perfectly agreeable is the Hungarian Sauvignon Blanc 1993 that is Pounds
2.99 at Safeway.
That same year has produced other fine Hungarian Sauvignons. Gyongyos Estate
enjoys wide distribution in the chains for around Pounds 3.49 and this is
the best vintage to date. Marks &amp; Spencer has another lively example at
Pounds 3.49 under the defiantly non-ethnic Deer Valley label. JR
                           *       *      *
Good news for diners from four of London's top hotels. The Causerie at
Claridge's has introduced a two-course dinner menu for Pounds 12 per person,
including VAT. A main course can be taken from the Smorgasbord or the hot
dish of the day and followed by pudding or cheese. For reservations phone
071-629-8860.
At The Dorchester there is a new menu in the Grill Room. A three-course set
lunch costs Pounds 23.50 including coffee, service and VAT and, as usual,
chef Willi Elsener will be concentrating on British food. From May 1, The
Terrace will be serving a Pounds 38 dine and dance package on Friday and
Saturday nights. Ring 071-629-8888.
The Ritz, too, is offering Friday and Saturday night dinner and dancing, to
big band sounds of the 1920s, 1930s and 1940s, from Pounds 33 a head. It is
also introducing a light lunch menu at the Palm Court. Prices start at
Pounds 12 per person and a glass of wine will be included in the lunch
price. Tel: 071-493-2687.
The Connaught is opening its Grill Room for dinner only on Saturdays and
Sundays. In addition to the a la carte menu a table d'hote will be served at
Pounds 35 a head plus 15 per cent service but including VAT. Tel:
071-466-7070. Jill James
                           *       *      *
More than 1,000 corkscrews from a single owner are to be auctioned at
Christie's South Kensington, London, on May 10 at 2pm. Collected over 30
years by Gianni Gachin, who died last year, the collection traces the
history of the corkscrew from the mid-18th century to the present day.
Oldest in the collection is a mid-18th century pocket folding corkscrew with
a seal bearing an effigy of Queen Anne.
The first English corkscrew ever patented, in 1795, designed by a London
clergyman called Samuel Henshall, is expected to fetch between Pounds 400
and Pounds 600. Viewing starts on May 3 at 9am. Tel: 071-321-3120/3121/3122
or fax: 071-581-3679. JJ
