FT  23 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: Your CGT allowances
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The table shows CGT indexation allowances for March. Multiply the original
cost of the asset by the figure for the month you bought it. Subtract the
result from the proceeds of your sale; the balance is your taxable gain or
loss. Say you bought shares for Pounds 6,000 in September 1985 and sold them
in March 1994 for Pounds 13,000. Multiplying the original cost by the
September 1985 figure of 1.493 gives a total of Pounds 8,958. Subtracting
that from the Pounds 13,000 gives a capital gain of Pounds 4,042, which is
within the 1993-94 CGT allowanace of Pounds 5,800. If selling shares bought
before April 6 1982, use the March 1982 figures. The Budget decision that
indexation cannot be used to create or increase a loss for shares sold after
November 29 1993 has now been modified by arrangements for Pounds 10,000 of
transitional relief (see Investors benefit).
