<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: The Palumbos - a family at war -
Trust expert Caroline Garnham explains the background to an extraordinary
court case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CAROLINE GARNHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Palumbo family wrangle is interesting for the points of law which are
likely to emerge concerning the difficult but important role of a
director/trustee. In this case, Lord Palumbo, Thomas Tharby and John
Underwood all are directors of Rugarth and/or one or more of its
subsidiaries, as well as being trustees of the Family Settlement.
There is nothing wrong with being a director as well as a trustee. In fact,
in some cases, judges have encouraged trustees actively to use their powers
as shareholders to put their man on the board. But the role of a director
who is a trustee as well is to protect the trust assets for all the
beneficiaries and is, therefore, significantly more onerous than that of a
director alone.
A company director is under an obligation to his company as determined by
company law - but only indirectly to the shareholders of that company who
have the power to remove him. On the other hand, a trustee of a family trust
must, under trust law, take 'such care as an ordinary, prudent man would
take if he were minded to make an investment for the benefit of other people
for whom he felt morally bound to provide.'
Furthermore, where a trust owns the majority of shares in a private company
 -such as the Palumbo Family Settlement and Rugarth - the law expects the
trustees to use their position of control to make sure that the company does
not start any project which is imprudent, hazardous, or wholly unsuitable
for a trust.
This does not mean that a trustee/director cannot make mistakes. Not all
investments go up in value; some inevitably go down.
So it is not enough for the plaintiffs to show that the Palumbo assets have
fallen in value. To succeed, the plaintiffs will have to prove that the
trustees did not pay due consideration to the protection of the trust
assets; did not ask themselves if the business policy of the company was
appropriate for the trust; or did not know enough to make the necessary
decisions.
The fact that trustees asked themselves the right questions and sought
proper advice - but then, for whatever reason (which need not be disclosed
to the beneficiaries) made, in hindsight, the wrong decision - is
immaterial.
Another aspect of the claim for the Palumbo trustees is that they benefited
personally from their position.
It is a basic legal rule that trustees cannot use their position for
personal benefit, regardless of how onerous or time-consuming their duties
may be.
Any financial benefits they obtain through exercising their powers as a
trustee must be returned to the trust fund.
There are, of course, exceptions to what otherwise would be a very harsh
rule. The first is that trustees can keep any benefits they receive from a
company if they obtained their position with it because of having a
shareholding of their own, or for other reasons that were not connected with
being a trustee.
A second is if they apply to court for an order stipulating that they can
keep their director's fees, remuneration or other benefits. In some cases,
the court will permit the director/trustee some benefit - provided that it
is not excessive.
The third area of trust law upon which the Palumbo case touches is the rule
that trustees exercising powers given to them in the trust deed must do so
with due consideration to all the facts of a case and the needs and
requirements of all the beneficiaries.
In this case, the trustees added the three children of Palumbo's second
marriage as beneficiaries to the Family Settlement. But such an action is
possible only if the deed contains a power for the trustees to do this. If
not, they will have breached trust and the court will act to rectify the
position. But if the trustees do have the power, the court's only interest
is whether it has been exercised properly.
Trustees must not let themselves be bullied by a beneficiary - or anyone
else - against their better judgment, even if that beneficiary is also a
trustee.
If trustees sign everything put in front of them without considering if this
is a proper exercise of their powers, then a court can ignore the trust's
paperwork, such as appointing new beneficiaries.
To date, however, the courts have not interfered in the decisions of
trustees except in extreme or exceptional circumstances.
Given the onerous obligations imposed on them, the restrictions on
trustee/directors, and the possible adverse publicity of a High Court action
if all goes wrong, some may wonder why anyone in their right mind would
create a family trust in the first place.
In many cases, the main reason is to preserve wealth in a tax-efficient way
for future generations. It must be remembered that, because of the Family
Settlement, the Palumbo family has preserved great wealth - and that the
assets in the Settlement escaped tax completely when Rudolph Palumbo died.
Caroline Garnham is a tax and trusts specialist at the legal firm of Simmons
&amp; Simmons
</TEXT>
