<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: Motorists who are driven to think
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Young and newly-qualified drivers could soon be rewarded with cheaper
insurance if they take further lessons.
The initiative comes from the Department of Transport and a group of
insurers. Extra lessons would cover areas such as driving on motorways, at
night and in poor weather, none of which is part of the present licence
test.
The move is part of several measures to improve accident rates for young
drivers - the commonly-quoted statistic is that those between 17 and 21 form
only 10 per cent of licence-holders but account for 20 per cent of
accidents.
Other measures announced already include compulsory re-testing for anyone
convicted of a motoring offence within two years of getting their licence
and a separate theory element in the driving test.
Insurers are also concerned that growing numbers of young people are driving
without insurance because they cannot afford the premiums; basic third-party
cover for a teenager can cost about Pounds 500 a year.
The industry estimates that at least one car in 10 is not insured, and the
burden of paying for accidents involving these falls on drivers who do have
cover through comprehensive premiums, and on levies to the Motor Insurers
Bureau. All drivers would benefit if younger motorists had fewer accidents
and cheaper insurance.
Full details of the government-led initiative are still being discussed but
some insurers have taken steps in the same direction already. One is General
Accident, which set up the Vantage scheme for new drivers with the British
School of Motoring.
Those who succeed in completing a Pounds 95 course are entitled to a
discount equivalent to one year's no-claims bonus on comprehensive insurance
with GA. As yet, though, such schemes are not widespread enough to encourage
significant numbers of young people to take the extra lessons.
RAC Insurance Services is lobbying insurers to take a more sympathetic
attitude to good younger drivers without insisting on extra training. It
suggests that new drivers who make no claims in their first year of driving
should be rewarded with a discount bigger than a standard one-year no-claims
bonus.
Younger drivers are often the focus of complaints about poor driving but
many experienced motorists could also benefit from further training.
Opinion surveys tend to show that the majority of drivers pride themselves
on their above-average skills. But anyone with a basic grasp of statistics
(and who has ever ventured on to a motorway) will realise that the survey
reveals little other than widespread self-delusion.
Advanced courses are not usually about skid-pan sessions or anti-hijack
techniques more appropriate to James Bond movies. The main idea is to make
drivers safer, more in control of their vehicles, and more observant in
ordinary driving conditions.
Thus, they are both less likely to cause accidents and can spot tricky
situations and erratic drivers from further away, so avoiding being the
victims of other people's poor driving.
The Institute of Advanced Motorists is the best-known arranger of advanced
driving courses and tests. Its members country-wide provide free training
leading up to the 90-minute advanced test, which costs Pounds 25. The pass
rate for those taking the course is 80 per cent. But only 60 per cent of
those confident enough to go straight for the test without the training pass
first time.
Members convicted of driving offences must tell the institute (in case they
do not, the IAM even has a team checking press cuttings for court reports).
But Ted Clements, its chief examiner, says: 'While our members certainly try
to respect the law, they are not holier than thou and they are not perfect
drivers - just safety conscious.'
The Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents has a very similar network
of volunteers offering training leading up to a test. And many commercial
organisations offer advanced driving courses although, of course, these will
be more expensive.
The IAM has links with one or two insurers and the RoSPA has a scheme with
Cornhill Insurance, but the rewards from taking an advanced test do not
necessarily result in cheaper insurance on the spot.
The few companies offering direct discounts may be at the more expensive end
of the market, and their discounted premiums could still be higher than
other insurers' standard levies. It is more likely to be that improved
skills help you to avoid accidents and, therefore, have an impact on your
no-claims bonus.
This is what has happened in the fleet insurance market. Increasingly,
companies insist that all those driving their cars complete an advanced
course. Experience has shown that accident rates can be cut by more than
half, leading to much-reduced premiums.
This does not necessarily work as effectively for private drivers, however;
a single non-blameworthy incident, such as a car being stolen or a
hit-and-run accident, can set their claims record back by several years.
To encourage more drivers, new and old, to take steps to improve their
driving, incentives need to be clearer and more immediate.
For further information, contact the Institute of Advanced Motorists at IAM
House, 359 Chiswick High Road, London W4 4HS (tel: 081-994 4403), or the
RoSPA Advanced Drivers Association, 22 Summer Road, Acocks Green, Birmingham
B27 7UT (021-706 8121).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6331 Fire, Marine, and Casualty Insurance.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COSTS  Product costs &amp; Product prices.
</TP>
