<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: Food for thought - The week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When Associated British Foods announces its interim results on Monday, they
are expected to show a small advance from Pounds 161m to about Pounds 167m,
before exceptional items. Investors will be looking for some indications on
plans for ABF's Pounds 500m cash pile, and clarification on the disposal
rumours surrounding Bakers Oven. Friday's agricultural feeds acquisition may
have been taken as a sign that the company plans to be more active on the
acquisition front. Meanwhile, the grocery and bread businesses are not
expected to show any great improvements. Farnell Electronics, the electronic
components group which paid Dollars 69.8m to acquire Multicomponents from
ITT in October, reports results for the year to January 31 on Monday. They
will be the first finals since Howard Poulson took over as chief executive
and pre-tax profits of between Pounds 47m and Pounds 48.5m are expected, up
from Pounds 41.6m the previous year when the figure was boosted by a Pounds
6.36m exceptional profit.
Tarmac, the UK's biggest construction and building materials group, reports
its results for 1993 on Tuesday with the markets expecting underlying
trading profits of between Pounds 50m to Pounds 53m, against about Pounds
21m the previous year. As with most construction companies to report
recently, FRS 3 provisions complicate the numbers. After goodwill
write-backs on disposals, the group is expected to report pre-tax losses of
Pounds 40m-Pounds 45m, compared with 1992's record losses of Pounds 350.3m.
When Sears, the UK's largest multiple speciality retailer, reports its
annual results on Tuesday, pre-tax profits are expected to have risen to
about Pounds 127m, up from last time's Pounds 83.5m which was struck after
net exceptional costs of Pounds 16.9m. The rise will be even more dramatic
on an FRS 3 basis, under which the group made pre-tax losses last time of
Pounds 47.8m after exceptional charges of Pounds 106.8m.
First-quarter figures on Thursday from ICI, a pure chemicals company since
the demerger from Zeneca last summer, will reflect both the company's
cost-cutting efforts and the health of the European bulk chemicals market.
Underlying trading is still tough in European chemicals with manufacturers
struggling to push through price increases.
But this will be more than made up for by the cost-cutting and the disposal
of the loss-making fibres operation in return for DuPont's acrylics
business. As a result, pre-tax profits of the chemicals businesses should
rise from last year's Pounds 63m to approaching Pounds 100m.
