<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US stocks mirror fall in bond
market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US blue-chip stocks dipped yesterday after the bond market failed to sustain
an early move upwards, but secondary indices improved, writes Frank McGurty
in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 3.86 lower at 3,648.68, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eased 1.10 to 447.63 in moderately
active trading.
However, the American SE composite gained 2.18 to 433.31, and the Nasdaq
composite added 3.82 to 722.56.
Stocks opened on a positive note, riding on momentum carried over from the
previous session's powerful rally. Early on, bonds were holding steady and
the flood of corporate results buffeting the market over the week slowed
considerably.
With no economic news to influence sentiment, Treasuries began to ebb by
mid-morning, after the market tested resistance levels and failed to break
through.
President Bill Clinton's appointment of Mr Alan Binder and Ms Janet Yellen
to fill two vacancies on the Federal Reserve Board was widely expected and
had little impact, even though there was some concern that they would dilute
its vigilance in fighting inflation.
Stocks mirrored the modest slump in bonds. Near midday, however, they moved
closer to their opening values in a convictionless updrift, briefly crossing
into positive territory before slipping again in the final hour.
Cyclical stocks were mixed, with International Paper down Dollars 1 at
Dollars 61 and 3M off Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 47 3/8 . Alcoa, up Dollars 1
at Dollars 67 3/4 , helped compensate for their losses. Elsewhere, Sears
gave back Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 46 1/2 after gaining ground on an
encouraging earnings report the previous session.
There were a few results out yesterday to inspire activity. Mobil gained
Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 78 3/8 . Its estimated first-quarter net income of
Dollars 1.31 a share, against Dollars 1.19 a year ago, beat expectations.
Texaco was Dollars 1 1/8 higher at Dollars 65. Kellogg was well ahead of
analysts' estimates, posting net income of 81 cents, against a consensus
forecast of 76 cents. But the share price flagged Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 51
1/2 in spite of an upgrading by NatWest Securities.
In the computer sector, Unisys dropped Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 11 5/8 after
disclosing that its worldwide orders were down in the last quarter.
On the Nasdaq, biotechnology stocks improved after Amgen, the sector's
bellwether, told analysts that its 1994 earnings projections were too
conservative. The issue jumped Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 42, while Chiron
climbed Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 59 5/8 and Biogen added Dollars 2 3/4 to
Dollars 35 3/4.
Canada
Toronto stocks ended steady in moderate trading. The TSE 300 composite index
slipped just 0.06 to 4,167.16 for a loss of about 73 on the week.
Advances led declines 417 to 389 and volume fell to 52.6m from 70.1m
yesterday. Trading value was CDollars 609.3m compared with CDollars 859.0m.
Eight of the 14 stocks groups rose and one was unchanged. Energy stocks
gained 1.48 per cent, consumer products, industrial products and mining also
rose, and banking and gold stocks fell 1 per cent and 1.75 per cent
respectively.
Brazil
Sao Paulo shares jumped 10.6 per cent in moderate trading, boosted by a
technically driven buying spree on blue chips after prices dropped for seven
sessions in a row. The Bovespa index closed 1,365 higher at 14,203 on
turnover of Crz264.1bn.
</TEXT>
