<DATE>940423
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity market stages strong
end-account rally - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK shares ended the week and the account in sparkling form as a powerful
performance by US stocks and bonds on Thursday evening and the emergence of
yet more takeover activity injected some much-needed confidence into the
market.
Even a lack-lustre opening performance by Wall Street yesterday failed to
discourage London.
Also helping the equity market regain its poise was a firm gilt-edged
market, where long-dated issues closed with gains of around  3/4 of a point
after money supply and lending figures for March.
Hard on the heels of the Lloyds Bank's Pounds 1.8bn merger with Cheltenham &amp;
Gloucester came news of a Pounds 177m takeover of Hogg Group, the insurance
broker, by Inchcape. A bid for Hogg had been widely expected after HSBC, the
banking group, acquired a 6 per cent stake some weeks ago. Inchcape was one
several potential bidders for Hogg and looked to have won control after
buying HSBC's stake.
The FT-SE 100 index, which came under severe pressure for much of the week,
rebounded strongly, closing a net 32.5 up at 3,133.7 and reducing the fall
on the five-day period to 34.6.
The market's second-tier stocks, comprising the FT-SE Mid 250 index, were
much more restrained with the index closing only a modest 7.0 higher at
3,789.5 in spite of some hefty two-way activity.
The London market has been hit by two big blows this week. First, the move
by the US Federal Reserve to increase its Fed Funds rate by a further
quarter of a point, and second, by evidence of strong economic growth which
is seen by the market as reducing the chances of any early cut in UK rates.
The main catalyst for yesterday's upsurge in London and throughout Europe
came from the US where the Dow Jones jumped 53 points or some 1.5 per cent
in the wake of a strong rally after excellent results from IBM, the computer
giant.
There was, however, some disappointment at the level of turnover in the
market given that sentiment was much improved following the big jump in US
markets and the latest bid news.
Turnover in London yesterday reached 816.2m shares but with the FT-SE 100
stocks only accounting for 317.1m shares, or 39 per cent of total business.
Electricity stocks, on the other hand, were badly affected by news that the
electricity industry regulator had sent out letters to the heads of all the
recs outlining what were said to be stringent and severe initial proposals
on pricing due to take effect next year.
Oil shares, among the market's best performers over the past couple of
weeks, made rapid progress in the wake of rising crude oil prices. The
majors responded to good results from Amoco, the US company, but the
market's attention remained firmly on exploration company Lasmo where there
was renewed takeover speculation and further big activity.
Much of this was carried via the inter-dealer broker screens which guarantee
anonymity to both buyer and seller of the shares and are widely utilised in
stake-building and takeover situations.
Marketmakers, although relieved at the market's resilience this week, said
they were not entirely convinced that the UK equity market's recent
correction had run its course. 'The market feels comfortable at this level
but becomes unhappy above 3,155 on the FT-SE 100; we remain at the mercy of
Wall Street.'
</TEXT>
