<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: ICI firm
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Previous strength on Wall Street helped ICI experience a sharp gain ahead of
first-quarter figures on Thursday. The shares were restrained in early
trading as NatWest Securities stressed its negative view.
However, they closed 24 1/2 higher at 829p with analysts expecting a profit
of between Pounds 80m and Pounds 100m on Thursday against a figure of Pounds
74m - restated for the demerger of Zeneca. There was some assistance from
Kleinwort Benson which has moved its recommendation to hold from sell.
There was no surprise that Hogg Group, the insurance group, finally
attracted a bid but there was surprise at the identity of the bidder.
The market had expected an offer to come from HSBC, the far eastern bank
whose shares had been marked down accordingly. In the event, the offer was
launched by Inchcape, the general trader, which then bought HSBC's 6.1 per
cent stake in Hogg at 257 1/2 p a share. Inchcape shares slipped 9 to 552p
on news of the Pounds 176.6m recommended cash offer at 255p a share. HSBC
rebounded almost 20 initially but settled 10 higher at 733p and Hogg, which
had risen from 133p at the start of the month, gained a further 23 to 257p.
Talk that Allied Lyons had lined up buyers for some of its food businesses
was again heard. Dalgety, off a penny at 445p, was being mooted as the most
likely purchaser of the ingredients business, while Associated British Foods
was being fingered as a candidate for the cake and biscuit business. The
shares bounced 17 to 598p, enhanced by a Pounds 35m agricultural business
deal, and ahead of figures on Monday. Allied Lyons rose 5 to 590p.
Reports that the deal to buy the Italian Ciga hotel chain was on the brink
of collapse, helped Forte shares advance 4 to 241p. The UK group had been
outbid for Ciga by ITT Sheraton, but was unlikely to return to the fray,
according to leisure analysts.
Among construction stocks Alfred McAlpine was strong, up 9 to 262p. The
company has been granted planning permission to build 3,330 homes and a
commercial development in Cambridgeshire. Elsewhere, Tarmac closed 7 higher
at 185p, ahead of results on Tuesday.
Eurotunnel fell 22 to 448p as reports circulated that its debt was trading
at a lower level.
The banking sector was still absorbing Lloyds Bank's Pounds 1.8bn takeover
of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society. Lloyds continued its rise, up
12 to 597p on turnover of 10m. Abbey National, one of the biggest mortgage
lenders, was worst hit by the probable increase in competition, dropping 14
1/2 to 432p; Credit Lyonnais Laing downgraded its 1996 forecast 28 per cent
to Pounds 871m. Other big mortgage lenders affected were Royal Bank of
Scotland, down 8 to 388p, and TSB, down 4 to 214p. There was also heavy
trade in Barclays, up 7 to 516p, and NatWest, down 3 1/2 to 442p.
The fortunes of TI shares improved after the engineering group held a
presentation on its aerospace subsidiary Dowty to analysts and institutions.
TI's price moved ahead 7 to 425p on trade of 1m shares.
Cazenove was said to have been behind the strong performance of BT whose
shares rose 8 1/2 to 391p. The partly paid added 7 1/2 at 272p.
The oil majors gave a robust performance in response to a surge in the price
of Brent crude and stronger than expected first-quarter figures from US
counterparts. BP improved 9 to 385 1/2 p and Shell Transport 14 to 725p.
Vodafone, badly affected at the start of the week by the forthcoming launch
of Hutchison Telecom's Orange mobile telephone system, continued to rally.
NatWest Securities and Hoare Govett led the recovery which drove Vodafone up
10 more to 522p yesterday after good turnover of 5.5m shares.
The insurance sector was pulled back by concerns over a television programme
scheduled for this weekend and expected to raise questions over asbestosis.
General Accident fell 12 to 594p and Commercial Union tumbled 14 to 574p,
while Royal Insurance and Sun Alliance slipped 5 to 259p and 3 to 329p
respectively.
