<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Markets Report: Dollar firmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The dollar finished firmer yesterday on foreign exchanges ahead of the
weekend G7 meeting of finance ministers and central bankers in Washington,
writes Philip Gawith.
Trading was mostly range-bound as dealers closed positions in order to
protect themselves against political comment emerging from the meeting which
could move the market.
Speculation about the possibility of some dollar supportive package emerging
from the G7 helped the US currency close in London at DM1.6947 from
DM1.6882. It was marginally firmer against the yen, closing at Y103.650 from
Y103.545.
The D-Mark closed unchanged at FFr3.427 against the French franc, but fell
to L956.7 from L958.4 against the Italian lira. The Spanish peseta firmed
after the central bank cut its key lending rate to 7.75 per cent from 8 per
cent, finishing at Pta81.37 from Pta81.44 against the D-Mark.
Although G7 meetings seldom produce any comment on currencies, markets were
slightly nervous on account of rumours throughout the week of concerted
central bank intervention to support the dollar against the yen. Recovery in
the US treasury market also lent support to the US currency.
Increasingly, though, the market is taking the view that if the dollar
breaches the key support level of Y102.50, then it is likely to fall below
Y100. Mr Mark Geddes, treasury economist at Midland Global Markets,
commented: 'I am sure the downside is going to be tested again.'
There was little response to the announcement of two economists, Mr Alan
Blinder and Ms Janet Yellen, to fill the vacancies on the board of the US
Federal Reserve. The nominations were expected.
German call money rose to 5.20/5.30 per cent, from 4.90/5.00 per cent
earlier, when the Bundesbank announced it was selling 5.30 per cent treasury
bills to put a floor on interest rates.
Analysts said the Bundesbank's action was a reminder to the market not to
overreach itself in terms of its interest rate expectations. Although the
central bank allowed the repo rate to fall by 12 basis points this week to
5.58 per cent, it now seems likely to return to a path of slow and steady
cuts.
In the futures market the June euromark contract closed three basis points
firmer at 94.75.
In the UK a stronger than expected M4 lending figure for March gave the
pound a small fillip, but it finished the day a pfennig lower at DM2.517
from DM2.527. It also finished more than a cent down against the dollar, at
Dollars 1.4853 from Dollars 1.4969.
Sterling futures had a slightly better day, with the June contract finishing
four basis points higher at 94.63. The market mood, however, remains very
bearish, with the December contract discounting three month money at 6.10
per cent at the end of the year. This involves interest rates rising nearly
1 percentage point from current levels.
Although a string of strong economic data has put a firm dampener on hopes
of a near-term rate cut, analysts believe the chance of rates rising soon is
also slight.
In the money markets the Bank of England comfortably dispatched a Pounds
1.1bn shortage.
</TEXT>
