FT  23 APR 94 / Economic Diary: Forward Events
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY: Greece's opposition New Democracy party congress in Halkidiki.
Taipei's nationalist central committee debates electoral reform. Yugoslavian
president Zoran Lilic in Romania signs political friendship treaty with
President Ion Iliescu.
TOMORROW: Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin visits Moscow. China's
premier Li Peng on tour of Turkmenistan, Uzbekhistan, Kyrgyzstan and
Mongolia.
MONDAY: European Union finance ministers meet in Luxembourg. European Union
farm ministers in Luxembourg discuss German request to ban imports of
cattle, beef and veal from Britain on grounds of possible BSE link.
Officials from Jordan, Lebanon and Syria at conference on Middle East travel
and tourism in Beirut. UK balance of trade figures with countries outside
EC. UK GDP first quarter (preliminary estimate). Anniversary celebrations in
Rome of Italy's wartime liberation.
TUESDAY: CBI industrial trends survey (April). UN biological weapons
inspectors return from Iraq. Sixth international conference on infectious
diseases in Prague. Thai Prime Minister Leekpai Chuan visits Japan.
WEDNESDAY: UK mortgage possession actions (first quarter). Bosnia's Moslem
president Alija Izetbegovic visits Romania. Europol meets in Athens to focus
on action against terrorism and drug dealing. Home Affairs Committee inquiry
into organised crime takes evidence from Home Office permanent secretary Sir
Clive Whitmore.
THURSDAY: Final day of South Africa's first all-race elections (results 48
hours after polls close). Opec secretary general Subroto speaks at
conference on World Energy in Transition in Dallas. Britain's Foreign
Secretary Douglas Hurd opens conference in London on financial markets in
Middle East. Energy trends (February). New vehicle registrations (March).
FRIDAY: UK economic trends (April). Monthly digest of statistics (April).
SPD state conference takes place in Mecklenburg, Germany.
