<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / International Company News: Exxon and Mobil lifted by
marketing activities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Exxon and Mobil, the two biggest US energy groups, more than offset lower
earnings from exploration and production in the first quarter with higher
profits in their refining and marketing activities. Non-operating items,
though, led Exxon to report a 2 per cent drop in net income from a year
before, while Mobil reported a 9 per cent increase.
Exxon's results were hampered by corporate and financing expenses of Dollars
270m, some Dollars 90m higher than a year before. The increase was due
primarily to foreign exchange fluctuations, the company said.
The depressed crude oil price, which was Dollars 4 below its level of a year
before, led to a fall in upstream exploration and production income outside
the US fell 12 per cent, to Dollars 590m. US upstream earnings, though, were
buoyed by higher natural gas prices and lower operating costs, and rose 7
per cent, to Dollars 245m.
The lower oil price supported margins in downstream refining and marketing
businesses, leading to earnings in the US of Dollars 39m, up from Dollars
21m a year before, and overseas of Dollars 349m, up from Dollars 277m.
Exxon's chemicals business reported improved results, thanks to higher
volumes and better margins. Earnings were Dollars 149m, up 21 per cent.
After the foreign exchange adjustments, though, Exxon reported net income
for the period of Dollars 1.16bn, or 92 cents a share, down from Dollars
1.185bn, or 94 cents a share, the year before.
Mobil, meanwhile, benefited from lower financing costs, which dropped
Dollars 35m to Dollars 73m, and a Dollars 12m fall in corporate and other
central expenses. These factors were largely behind the Dollars 45m rise in
after-tax profits during the period, to Dollars 535m. Earnings per share
rose 12 cents to Dollars 1.31.
Earnings from Mobil's operations grew only slightly from a year before, with
upstream income falling Dollars 98m, to Dollars 335m, and downstream
earnings rising Dollars 102m, to Dollars 236m.
</TEXT>
