<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 94 / Building Societies - Shifting ground: Support grows for Bank
of England regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Treasury ministers and senior officials are supporting proposals to transfer
supervision of big building societies to the Bank of England. The move has
been among ideas mooted in a government review of society legislation.
A decision on the transfer of responsibilities for big societies from the
Building Societies Commission to the Bank of England has been given added
urgency by Lloyds Bank's proposed Pounds 1.8bn acquisition of the Cheltenham
and Gloucester Building Society.
That deal has highlighted the increasing similarity between the activities
of big building societies and those of the clearing banks.
Government officials expect more society takeovers and feel it would be far
more efficient for one supervisor, probably the Bank of England, to decide
whether depositors' interests would be best served by a takeover.
'There is a strong logic for financial institutions to be regulated
according to their functions rather than their corporate structure', a
senior Whitehall official said.
Banks increasingly regard the bigger societies ranging from the Bradford and
Bingley with Pounds 14bn of assets to the Halifax with Pounds 67bn, as their
competitors.
Small societies, friendly societies and credit unions would remain the
responsibility of the Building Societies Commission.
Mr John Watts, chairman of the Commons Treasury and Civil Service Committee,
said Lloyds' proposed takeover raised the question of whether banks should
be regulated separately from building societies. The committee's inquiry
into regulation may recommend that there should be one regulator for banks
and big building societies.
At present, the Commission supervises 6,000 mutual societies - or
institutions owned by their borrowing and lending members - most of them
tiny. The Bank of England is responsible for banks, which have a corporate
status.
Bank of England and Treasury officials believe there are too many building
societies and are convinced that the most promising route for securing
rationalisation is to allow banks to buy the weaker societies.
The Treasury may put pressure on the Building Societies Commission not to
put unnecessary obstacles in the way of bank acquisitions of societies.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour's City spokesman, called for the regulatory
system to be overhauled. 'We need a proper framework to govern mergers
between banks and building societies to ensure competition and consumer
protection.'
See Weekend FT, Page III and Men in the News, Features
</TEXT>
