<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Bonds: Doubt keeps issuers away
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New issuance in the Eurobond market ground to a halt yesterday as continued
uncertainty in the secondary markets pushed issuers and investors back to
the sidelines.
A news agency report from New York that Hanson, the Anglo-American
conglomerate, was considering a global bond offering of Dollars 1bn or more
enlivened the market in the afternoon. Although the Hanson rumour has
surfaced before, the report came as a surprise to most London-based
syndicate managers yesterday.
Hanson declined to comment on the report.
Some syndicate managers say the rumour may have been triggered by news that
Quantum Chemical Corporation, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hanson, planned
to redeem some more bonds.
Hanson said the redemption of these bonds would complete the refinancing of
all Quantum's public or privately-placed debt, and bring to Dollars 2.5bn
the amount of such debt it will have redeemed or repurchased since it was
acquired by Hanson.
Quantum plans to redeem, on May 22, all of its 6 per cent subordinated
exchangeable debentures due May 2011. Calculated on principal amounts, there
are currently Dollars 46.3m of debentures outstanding.
Elsewhere, Halifax Building Society took advantage of investor demand to
increase Wednesday's offering of capped floating-rate notes, to Pounds 150m
from an original amount of Pounds 100m. The four-year notes were trading at
99.52 yesterday afternoon, up from a re-offer price of 99.50.
