<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Company News: Westinghouse income falls to
Dollars 36m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Net income at Westinghouse Electric, the troubled US conglomerate, fell to
Dollars 36m in the first quarter from the previous year's Dollars 59m before
accounting changes, the company reported yesterday.
The decline came in spite of a one-time gain of Dollars 10m before tax from
the sale of two radio stations. But the company had warned in January that
the figures would be much lower, and the shares put on Dollars  1/2 to close
at Dollars 11 1/2 .
Sales were down to Dollars 1.74bn from Dollars 2.02bn last time and
operating profits were down to Dollars 65m from Dollars 146m. Earnings per
share were 7 cents, down from 14 cents before accounting changes.
The figures were hit by increased pension costs of Dollars 33m and reduced
licensee income of Dollars 15m. The previous year benefited from a Dollars
25m change in accounting for nuclear fuel revenues.
Mr Mike Jordan, chairman and chief executive, said progress was made on a
number of strategic initiatives. Its financial structure had been
strengthened through last month's Dollars 520m preferred equity issue, and
the company had received Dollars 1.4bn from the sale of its distribution and
control business and the Westinghouse Electric Supply Company. Net debt was
down to Dollars 3.3bn at the end of the quarter from Dollars 5.1bn at the
beginning.
Broadcasting, government and environmental services, Thermo King and WCI
Communities improved financial contributions. Electronic systems and energy
systems made lower contributions while power generation, The Knoll Group and
other businesses increased their losses.
</TEXT>
