<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Company News: Amoco weathers drop in oil price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Amoco, the Chicago-based energy company, yesterday reported a net profit of
Dollars 398m for the first quarter, up from a Dollars 343m a year ago. The
rise was posted in spite of lower oil prices. Revenues were Dollars 6.7bn,
down slightly from Dollars 6.9bn in the same quarter of 1993.
Mr Laurance Fuller, chairman, said cost-cutting and restructuring had
allowed Amoco to post stronger earnings in spite of a 'Dollars 4-to-Dollars
5-per-barrel' drop in crude oil prices. However, he said further changes to
corporate structure were required to keep Amoco competitive.
Lower oil prices were partly offset by a 66 per cent jump in profits, to
Dollars 90m, at Amoco's chemical business. Refining, marketing and
transportation earnings also rose, to Dollars 104m from Dollars 80m a year
earlier.
Income for exploration and production operations in the US, however, were
lower than a year ago, at Dollars 207m against Dollars 253m. This was
primarily because of the drop in crude oil prices. Earnings from Amoco's
overseas exploration and production operations also declined, to Dollars
61m.
Worldwide capital and exploration spending dropped to Dollars 357m from
Dollars 381m a year ago.
</TEXT>
