<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Company News: Northwest Airlines bucks trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Northwest Airlines, the US carrier that returned to the stock market last
month after being taken private five years earlier, yesterday reported net
income of Dollars 18.3m in its first quarter, compared with net losses of
Dollars 100.3m last time.
The profit was in sharp contrast with the losses reported a day earlier by
American Airlines and USAir, which said they had been hit by severe winter
weather and low fares.
However, Northwest's figures were flattered by two non-trading items. It
gained Dollars 9.2m before tax from an accounting item related to its
employee stock ownership plan, and a Dollars 12.7m cut in depreciation
expenses following a revaluation of some of its aircraft.
Operating revenues rose 5 per cent to Dollars 2.13bn and earnings per share
were 5 cents, compared with losses of Dollars 1.86 last time.
One reason Northwest's figures did not suffer as badly of those of American
Airlines and USAir is that its route structure is not concentrated in the
north-east of the US, where the worst of the weather struck.
The airline is also benefiting from wage and benefit concessions worth
Dollars 886m over the next three years, under an agreement with its
employees which will give them a 27.4 per cent stake in the company.
Southwest Airlines, the most profitable airline in the US, reported
first-quarter net income of Dollars 41.8m, an increase of 68 per cent on the
comparable period's Dollars 24.9m before accounting changes.
</TEXT>
